\section{presentation 12/12/13}
\label{sec-2}
TITLE: Evaluation of Pitch-Class Set Similarity Measures for Tonal Analysis
\subsection{Motivation}
\label{sec-2-1}
\begin{itemize}
\item there are many of these measure from mathematics and pitch class set theory but their practical value is not well known outside highly theoretical circles
\item in MIR for example the more commonly used similarity measures have little or no musical or perceptual relevance for example euclidean distance
\item many people in MIR and other areas might be put off by the apparent complexity of this mathematics
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Goal}
\label{sec-2-2}
\begin{itemize}
\item the goal is to therefore provide some characterisation of these measures that is widely relevant to many applications in tonal analysis
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Methodology}
\label{sec-2-3}
\begin{itemize}
\item the way this will be done will be first to thoroughly survey all the relevant techniques and specific capabilities
\item then to look closely at their implicit pitch-spaces via MDS
\item this is a method of mapping a geomtric spaces based on the relative distance between a collection of objects
\item most important will be to try and find low dimensional projections of these spaces for visualisation (which is always a useful thing)
\item and also to characterise the local stress of these projections, so how distorted do they become when you reduce the dimensionality
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Evaluation}
\label{sec-2-4}
\begin{itemize}
\item finally for evaluation it will be necessary to try and use these spaces for some analysis.
\item so, I will attempt to integrate them with the work that Agustin has been doing and his framework for tonal analysis
\item and with this we can perform case studies using real musical examples that already have been subjected to some analysis so we have something to reference and compare with with
\end{itemize}
\section{Similarity Measures}
\label{sec-3}
\subsection{intro}
\label{sec-3-1}
\begin{itemize}
\item the problem of how to assess similarity of pc-set-classes
\item variety of similarity measures have been proposed over the years (\texttt{see the list})
\begin{itemize}
\item and arguments about the merits of these measures now occupy a number of journal pages.
\item Surveys/critiques of most measures can be found in \texttt{Castren}, \texttt{Isaacson}, and \texttt{Scott \& Isaacson}
\end{itemize}
\item Some fundamental questions remain unresolved:
\begin{enumerate}
\item What constitutes a "good" measure of pcset similarity?
\begin{itemize}
\item one that mirrors our "musical intuitions"?
\item See \texttt{Quinn, 2001} and \texttt{Isaacson, 1996} for discussion of issues
\end{itemize}
\item what musical properties does each function measure?
\begin{itemize}
\item this question is more readily amenable to analysis and should be answered first
\item This question is approached by \texttt{Samplaski}
\end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}
\end{itemize}

