\section{MDS on Pcsets using distance function}
\label{sec-4}
\begin{itemize}
\item resulting geometries will tell us something about what properties of pcsets the functions are measuring
\item if the geometries produced by different functions match up save for rotation, translation, or reflection, then,
\begin{itemize}
\item either a) measuring the same constructs, whatever those might be
\item or b) measuring constructs that, while different, are themselves functions of some other underlying construct(s)
\end{itemize}
\item Only such functions as give distinct proximity/distance ratings can be so evaluated (not \texttt{Rn})
\item interval-class vector or subset
\item matrices of ratings will be symmetrical
\begin{itemize}
\item configurations might be reflections or rotations of each other
\item require a reference function to compare with
\item use simplest MDS which is result-invariant with respect to axial reflection and rotation
\item Procrustes rotation (\texttt{Samplaski} paragraph 28)
\end{itemize}
\item no noise
\begin{itemize}
\item measures are formal abstract functions
\end{itemize}
\item dimensionality of solutions depends on how many data points \texttt{samplaski} paragraph 33
\end{itemize}

\section{Castren, 1994\hfill{}\textsc{RECREL:%REL}}
\label{sec-5}
\begin{itemize}
\item uses subset content
